Here's how to save and restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Save draft when app backgrounds
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm is not null)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Restore draft when app returns
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm is not null)
                vm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        };

        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm is not null)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        };

        return window;
    }

    private NoteViewModel? GetNoteViewModel()
    {
        if (Windows.FirstOrDefault()?.Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
            return vm;
        return null;
    }
}
```

**2. Your ViewModel (simplified):**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = string.Empty;
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Guidance |
|---------|----------|
| Where to save | `Stopped` â€” fires when the app is no longer visible |
| Where to restore | `Resumed` â€” fires when returning from background |
| Android back button | Also save in `Destroying` (it can skip `Stopped`) |
| Keep it fast | `Preferences` is ideal for small text; avoid DB writes here |
| First launch | `Resumed` does **not** fire on first launch â€” load initial state in your page's `OnAppearing` or constructor |

**3. Clear saved draft after the user explicitly saves the note:**

```csharp
public void SaveNote()
{
    // persist to your database/service...
    Preferences.Remove("draft_text");
}
```

This pattern ensures no draft is lost even if the OS terminates your app while backgrounded.
